# Nexus instead of broad grep (Python)

## Design goal (short)

In **large Python repos**, **blind text search** (`grep`/`rg`/Select-String) as a first step is **token-expensive** and tends to produce low-signal raw hit lines. **Nexus** builds the map and exposes a **query interface**.

**Rule:** The agent should **not search by itself**. It should send questions to Nexus and let Nexus return **where to read**.

**Security / freshness:** default to **fresh rebuild** per query (no persistent cache). If a cached mode exists, it must be an explicit opt-in and treated as **security-sensitive**.

**Control header (recommended):** enable control headers so the agent always sees the active Nexus policy before the answer:
- CLI: `--control-header`
- Env: `NEXUS_CONTROL_HEADER=1`

**Tiering (default for agents):** **`nexus <path> --agent-mode -q "..."`** (structural compact slice: `agent_compact` + **minimal** fields + cap **10**, overridable) → **`read_file`** (tiny slice) → STOP. Alternatives: **`nexus-grep <path> -q "..."`** (thin map search) or **`nexus --names-only`**.  
Escalate when required: plain **`nexus -q "…"`** (**`llm_brief`**, richer text) for narrative depth; **`nexus -q "impact …"`** / **`why …`** / mutation chains; **`nexus --json`** only for explicit full-graph export.

**Canonical perspectives (stable agent vocabulary):** `nexus` supports **`--perspective NAME`** with the same string values as the library’s `PerspectiveKind` (`heuristic_slice`, `llm_brief`, `query_slice_json`, `agent_names`, `agent_symbol_lines`, **`agent_compact`**, `trust_detail`, `focus_graph`, `mutation_trace`). Use **`--center-kind`** + **`--center-ref`** for symbol-centered views; **`--mutation-key`** for `mutation_trace`. **`--perspective` must not** be combined with legacy output switches (`--names-only`, `--query-slice-json`, `--trace-mutation`, `--focus-graph`, `--json`) in one invocation — pick one style. Legacy shortcuts remain valid and equivalent where documented.

**`--agent-mode`:** one flag → **`agent_compact`** + **`--compact-fields minimal`** + **`--max-symbols` 10** unless you pass those explicitly; incompatible with `--json` / `--names-only` / etc. Prefer this as the **first structural** query in agent loops when you want **parse-friendly** output.

**`--compact-fields`:** only with **`--perspective agent_compact`**. Presets **`minimal`** / **`standard`** / **`full`**, or comma-list (`meta`, `calls`, `writes`, `called_by`, `reads`, `tags`, `next_open`). Omitted = **full** (verbose compact).

**`--metrics-json`:** stderr line **`[NEXUS_METRICS] {…}`** after success — use for benchmarks and regression (`output_tokens_tiktoken`, `compact_fields`, `agent_mode`, slice stats). Env: **`NEXUS_METRICS_JSON=1`**.

**Epistemic rule:** **`heuristic_slice`** is only the **heuristic** symbol pick (table/slice path). **`llm_brief`** may use **special query modes** (`impact`, `why`, …). For the same `-q`, those two can **differ by design** — do not assume the slice list equals the brief’s symbol set. For impact/why/mutation-chain style questions, prefer **`llm_brief`** (or plain `nexus -q …`, which is the same brief path).

**Debug (optional):** **`--debug-perspective`** prints one JSON line per render to **stderr** (`payload_kind`, `advice`, `provenance`); **stdout** stays pipe-clean.

Full requirement matrix (upstream): **`docs/cli-perspective.md`** in the Nexus repo; verify with **`nexus --help`** if your installed version exposes `--perspective`. Patch-style reports: **`docs/patchnotes/README.md`**.

## CLI catalog (what to run when)

| Goal | Command pattern (conceptual) |
|------|------------------------------|
| **Fast structural orientation** (default agent path) | `nexus <path> --agent-mode -q "<topic or identifiers>"` |
| **Even thinner** name list | `nexus <path> -q "…" --names-only [--annotate] --max-symbols N` |
| **Wrapped search** (bounded symbols) | `nexus-grep <path> -q "…" --max-symbols N` |
| **Rich narrative + special modes** | `nexus <path> -q "impact Class"` / `why …` / `full mutation chain` ( **`llm_brief`** ) |
| **Explicit perspective** | `nexus <path> --perspective heuristic_slice -q "…"` vs `agent_compact` vs `llm_brief` (see matrix in `docs/cli-perspective.md`) |
| **Per-run telemetry** | append **`--metrics-json`** (or env); batch: **`extras/nexus_benchmark.py`** on Nexus checkout |
| **Safe-by-default exploration** | **`nexus-policy <path> -q "…"`** |

**Canonical template:** Shipped with **`nexus-inference`** (Python package `nexus`, module **`nexus.cursor_rules`**). **CLI commands:** **`nexus`**, **`nexus-grep`**, **`nexus-policy`**, **`nexus-cursor-rules`**, **`nexus-console`** — there is **no** shell command `nexus-inference`. **Install into a target repo:** run **`nexus-cursor-rules install`** at the project root — writes this `.mdc` to **`<target-repo>/.cursor/rules/`** (Cursor loads rules from there). Print bundled directory: **`nexus-cursor-rules --path`**. Overwrite: **`nexus-cursor-rules install --force`**. Same via **`python -m nexus.cursor_rules`** with the same arguments. Optional global: `%USERPROFILE%\.cursor\rules\` (User Rules). When developing Nexus, source lives at **`src/nexus/cursor_rules/nexus-over-grep.mdc`**.

---

On a **reference machine** the same logic can be **global**: `%USERPROFILE%\.cursor\rules\nexus-python-context.mdc` (same content as this file; adjust paths to your Nexus checkout if needed).

When you need to understand **Python code, calls, mutations, or architecture**, prefer **`nexus --agent-mode`**, **`nexus-grep`**, or **`nexus -q`** for map queries first. Do **not** use `grep`/`rg`/Select-String for “orientation”.

## Why

- `nexus` returns **symbols, edges, layer, mutation paths, confidence** → more compact answers.
- Map-query answers can be kept **bounded** via `--max-symbols` and `--names-only`.
- **`--names-only --annotate`:** one line per primary symbol (`qualified_name | confidence | tags | layer | file:line`); plain `-q` briefs add **`NEXT_OPEN`** file:line hints and fold **duplicate simple names** (`SAME_NAME` / `same_name_also`). Default query slice cap if `--max-symbols` is omitted: **12**.

## Default flow

1. Choose repo root or package path (e.g. `.` or `src/mypkg`).
2. **Unknown or large codebase:** orient with **few tokens first** by querying the map:
   - **Preferred (agents):** `nexus <path> --agent-mode -q "<topic or identifiers>"`, or
   - `nexus-grep <path> -q "<topic>" --max-symbols 25`, or
   - `nexus <path> -q "<topic>" --names-only --max-symbols 40`, or `--names-only --annotate` for one-liners with confidence/tags.
3. If more context is needed: **tighter** follow-up query (identifiers from step 2), or switch to **`nexus -q`** ( **`llm_brief`** ) for narrative / **`impact`** / **`why`**; keep **`--max-symbols`** small.
4. Full graph only when explicitly needed: `nexus <path> --json > graph.json`

## Agent workflow (Cursor): closed loop

The model **drives context acquisition** (hypothesis → tool → evidence → refine). Default path:

1. **Orient:** `nexus … --agent-mode -q "..."` when you want **structured** calls/writes; or `nexus-grep … -q "..."` (thin); or `nexus … --names-only` (names only).
2. **From hits:** derive concrete symbols/paths/files.
3. **Deepen:** targeted **`read_file`** (relevant blocks only) **or** a second, tighter `nexus-grep` / `nexus -q` query with **identifiers** from step 2.
4. **Structure/chains only if needed:** `nexus -q "…"` with **small** `--max-symbols` (e.g. 15–25) and explicit operators like `impact` / `why`.
5. **Full graph** only for explicit need or hard architecture questions: `nexus <path> --json > graph.json`

**Text search:** do **not** use raw `grep`/`rg`/Select-String in Python repos. If you need search, use **`nexus-grep`** (wrapped) or ask a better `nexus -q` query.

Note: the implementation may use additional internal helpers, but the agent-facing behavior is: **query the map (`nexus --agent-mode` / `nexus-grep` / `nexus -q`)**.

